{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781756768628,"sessionID":"ses_1270761dbffecw7Dfym5Wp50VJ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Mu9bhifioWvls1lgWyK43WLC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/review_core.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/review_core.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Review Core Doctrine\n3: description: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"findings first severity ordering\"\n6:   - \"review finding schema\"\n7:   - \"severity contract for merge decisions\"\n8:   - \"evidence file line citation\"\n9:   - \"baseline surface precedence\"\n10:   - \"baseline check families\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Review Core Doctrine\n16: \n17: Shared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\n24: \n25: ---\n26: \n27: ## 2. SEVERITY DEFINITIONS\n28: \n29: | Level | Meaning | Handling |\n30: | --- | --- | --- |\n31: | P0 | Blocker: exploitable security issue, auth bypass, destructive data loss | Block merge |\n32: | P1 | Required: correctness bug, spec mismatch, must-fix gate issue | Fix before merge |\n33: | P2 | Suggestion: non-blocking improvement, documentation polish, style or maintainability follow-up | Optional or schedule follow-up |\n34: \n35: Escalation rule: if confidence is low but impact is high, classify toward the higher severity and state the uncertainty explicitly.\n36: \n37: ### Numeric Severity Calibration\n38: \n39: Numeric scores are advisory context, not the gate. A reviewer may add an optional `riskScore` to a finding and adjust it by `+/-2` for local context such as exploitability, blast radius, user impact, confidence, or proven containment. The merge/block decision remains the severity contract above: `P0` blocks, `P1` requires remediation, and `P2` is advisory. Do not adopt `score>=4` or any numeric threshold as a blocker.\n40: \n41: ---\n42: \n43: ## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n44: \n45: - Every `P0` and `P1` finding must include a concrete `file:line` citation.\n46: - Evidence must tie the finding to observed code behavior, not just a general concern.\n47: - `P2` findings should still include specific evidence when available, even if impact is advisory.\n48: - If evidence is incomplete, state the assumption and why the risk still matters.\n49: \n50: ---\n51: \n52: ## 4. FINDINGS OUTPUT ORDERING\n53: \n54: - Present findings before summary or praise sections.\n55: - Order findings by severity first: `P0`, then `P1`, then `P2`.\n56: - Keep ordering stable within a severity bucket by impact and confidence.\n57: - Separate required fixes from optional suggestions so merge decisions stay clear.\n58: \n59: ---\n60: \n61: ## 5. BASELINE + SURFACE PRECEDENCE\n62: \n63: Apply this skill as the baseline first, then pair it with `sk-code` surface evidence when available:\n64: \n65: - Detected code surface -> `sk-code:<surface>`\n66: - Unclear surfaces -> baseline-only plus explicit uncertainty\n67: \n68: Precedence rules:\n69: \n70: - Baseline security and correctness minimums are always enforced.\n71: - Surface style, process, build, and test conventions override generic baseline guidance.\n72: - Unclear conflicts must be escalated rather than guessed.\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ## 6. BASELINE CHECK FAMILIES\n77: \n78: Mandatory baseline families:\n79: \n80: - Correctness minimums: regression risk, contract safety, spec mismatch, destructive side effects, and boundary handling.\n81: - Security minimums: auth and authorization gaps, injection exposure, unsafe secrets handling, privilege misuse, and reliability risks with security impact.\n82: \n83: These minimums cannot be relaxed by surface guidance.\n84: \n85: ---\n86: \n87: ## 7. FINDING SCHEMA\n88: \n89: Each finding should provide:\n90: \n91: | Field | Requirement |\n92: | --- | --- |\n93: | `id` | Stable label within the review report, such as `P1-001` |\n94: | `severity` | One of `P0`, `P1`, `P2` |\n95: | `title` | Short, risk-oriented summary |\n96: | `file` | Primary `path:line` location |\n97: | `evidence` | Plain-language explanation tied to observed code |\n98: | `findingClass` | One of `instance-only`, `class-of-bug`, `cross-consumer`, `algorithmic`, `matrix/evidence`, or `test-isolation` |\n99: | `scopeProof` | Grep/test/audit evidence that the recommendation covers same-class sites and consumers, or proves the finding is instance-only |\n100: | `affectedSurfaceHints` | Optional string array of producer/consumer surfaces the fix should address; recommended for actionable findings, required for cross-consumer findings. Use free-form short strings, max about 5 entries. Optional for instance-only findings. |\n101: | `riskScore` | Optional advisory number for relative risk calibration; never gating and never a substitute for `severity` |\n102: | `recommendation` | Specific, scope-proportional fix or follow-up |\n103: \n104: Suggested shape:\n105: \n106: ```markdown\n107: ### P1-001 [P1] Missing authorization check\n108: - File: path/to/file.ts:42\n109: - Evidence: Request handling reaches the write path before role validation.\n110: - Finding class: cross-consumer\n111: - Scope proof: `rg -n \"permission guard|write path\" path/to` shows the write handler is the only unchecked consumer.\n112: - Affected surface hints: [\"request handler\", \"write path\", \"permission guard\"]\n113: - riskScore: 6 (advisory only)\n114: - Recommendation: Enforce the existing permission guard before mutation.\n115: ```\n116: \n117: ---\n118: \n119: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n120: \n121: - [review_ux_single_pass.md](./review_ux_single_pass.md) - Interactive single-pass report flow and next-step prompts.\n122: - [quick_reference.md](./quick_reference.md) - Lightweight index across baseline review references.\n123: - [security_checklist.md](../assets/security_checklist.md) - Security and reliability checks.\n124: - [code_quality_checklist.md](../assets/code_quality_checklist.md) - Correctness, KISS, DRY, and maintainability checks.\n125: \n126: ---\n\n(End of file - total 126 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Review Core Doctrine\ndescription: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"findings first severity ordering\"\n  - \"review finding schema\"\n  - \"severity contract for merge decisions\"\n  - \"evidence file line citation\"\n  - \"baseline surface precedence\"\n  - \"baseline check families\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\n---\n\n# Review Core Doctrine\n\nShared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/review_core.md","text":"---\ntitle: Review Core Doctrine\ndescription: Shared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"findings first severity ordering\"\n  - \"review finding schema\"\n  - \"severity contract for merge decisions\"\n  - \"evidence file line citation\"\n  - \"baseline surface precedence\"\n  - \"baseline check families\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\n---\n\n# Review Core Doctrine\n\nShared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nShared findings-first review doctrine for both single-pass and deep-review workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SEVERITY DEFINITIONS\n\n| Level | Meaning | Handling |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| P0 | Blocker: exploitable security issue, auth bypass, destructive data loss | Block merge |\n| P1 | Required: correctness bug, spec mismatch, must-fix gate issue | Fix before merge |\n| P2 | Suggestion: non-blocking improvement, documentation polish, style or maintainability follow-up | Optional or schedule follow-up |\n\nEscalation rule: if confidence is low but impact is high, classify toward the higher severity and state the uncertainty explicitly.\n\n### Numeric Severity Calibration\n\nNumeric scores are advisory context, not the gate. A reviewer may add an optional `riskScore` to a finding and adjust it by `+/-2` for local context such as exploitability, blast radius, user impact, confidence, or proven containment. The merge/block decision remains the severity contract above: `P0` blocks, `P1` requires remediation, and `P2` is advisory. Do not adopt `score>=4` or any numeric threshold as a blocker.\n\n---\n\n## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Every `P0` and `P1` finding must include a concrete `file:line` citation.\n- Evidence must tie the finding to observed code behavior, not just a general concern.\n- `P2` findings should still include specific evidence when available, even if impact is advisory.\n- If evidence is incomplete, state the assumption and why the risk still matters.\n\n---\n\n## 4. FINDINGS OUTPUT ORDERING\n\n- Present findings before summary or praise sections.\n- Order findings by severity first: `P0`, then `P1`, then `P2`.\n- Keep ordering stable within a severity bucket by impact and confidence.\n- Separate required fixes from optional suggestions so merge decisions stay clear.\n\n---\n\n## 5. BASELINE + SURFACE PRECEDENCE\n\nApply this skill as the baseline first, then pair it with `sk-code` surface evidence when available:\n\n- Detected code surface -> `sk-code:<surface>`\n- Unclear surfaces -> baseline-only plus explicit uncertainty\n\nPrecedence rules:\n\n- Baseline security and correctness minimums are always enforced.\n- Surface style, process, build, and test conventions override generic baseline guidance.\n- Unclear conflicts must be escalated rather than guessed.\n\n---\n\n## 6. BASELINE CHECK FAMILIES\n\nMandatory baseline families:\n\n- Correctness minimums: regression risk, contract safety, spec mismatch, destructive side effects, and boundary handling.\n- Security minimums: auth and authorization gaps, injection exposure, unsafe secrets handling, privilege misuse, and reliability risks with security impact.\n\nThese minimums cannot be relaxed by surface guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 7. FINDING SCHEMA\n\nEach finding should provide:\n\n| Field | Requirement |\n| --- | --- |\n| `id` | Stable label within the review report, such as `P1-001` |\n| `severity` | One of `P0`, `P1`, `P2` |\n| `title` | Short, risk-oriented summary |\n| `file` | Primary `path:line` location |\n| `evidence` | Plain-language explanation tied to observed code |\n| `findingClass` | One of `instance-only`, `class-of-bug`, `cross-consumer`, `algorithmic`, `matrix/evidence`, or `test-isolation` |\n| `scopeProof` | Grep/test/audit evidence that the recommendation covers same-class sites and consumers, or proves the finding is instance-only |\n| `affectedSurfaceHints` | Optional string array of producer/consumer surfaces the fix should address; recommended for actionable findings, required for cross-consumer findings. Use free-form short strings, max about 5 entries. Optional for instance-only findings. |\n| `riskScore` | Optional advisory number for relative risk calibration; never gating and never a substitute for `severity` |\n| `recommendation` | Specific, scope-proportional fix or follow-up |\n\nSuggested shape:\n\n```markdown\n### P1-001 [P1] Missing authorization check\n- File: path/to/file.ts:42\n- Evidence: Request handling reaches the write path before role validation.\n- Finding class: cross-consumer\n- Scope proof: `rg -n \"permission guard|write path\" path/to` shows the write handler is the only unchecked consumer.\n- Affected surface hints: [\"request handler\", \"write path\", \"permission guard\"]\n- riskScore: 6 (advisory only)\n- Recommendation: Enforce the existing permission guard before mutation.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- [review_ux_single_pass.md](./review_ux_single_pass.md) - Interactive single-pass report flow and next-step prompts.\n- [quick_reference.md](./quick_reference.md) - Lightweight index across baseline review references.\n- [security_checklist.md](../assets/security_checklist.md) - Security and reliability checks.\n- [code_quality_checklist.md](../assets/code_quality_checklist.md) - Correctness, KISS, DRY, and maintainability checks.\n\n---","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":126,"totalLines":126,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/review_core.md","time":{"start":1781756768623,"end":1781756768626}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_02bd07ebb5b62c7d016a3373605f34819187a458b2249fd3d1"}},"id":"prt_ed8fab166001Dw2T7hqd8IkJ28","sessionID":"ses_1270761dbffecw7Dfym5Wp50VJ","messageID":"msg_ed8fa8b9e001SF59c54uHYt6Ew"}}
